- in in which one person or group can win something only by causing another person or group to lose it

Author: toorielle
Content:
gangway [n.] - a raised platform or walkway providing a passage
- <BRITISH> a passage between rows of seats, especially in a theater or aircraft
- a movable bridge linking a ship to the shore
- an opening in the bulwarks by which a ship is entered or left

Author: toorielle
Content: fender pile [n.] - an outside row of piles that protects a pier or wharf from damage by ships

Author: toorielle
Content:
pique [v.] - stimulate (interest or curiosity)
- feel irritated or resentful
- <ARCHAIC> pride oneself

Author: toorielle
Content:
skeletonize [v.] - to reduce to a skeleton or a bare framework
- to outline or sketch (a story, report, etc.) briefly
- to reduce (a work force, etc.) greatly in number or size

Author: toorielle
Content:
downy [adj.] - covered with fine soft hair or feathers
- filled with soft feathers
- soft and fluffy

Author: toorielle
Content:
attestation [n.] - evidence or proof of something
- a declaration that something exists or is the case
- the action of being a witness to or formally certifying something

Author: toorielle
Content:
ellipsis [n.] - the omission of one or more words that are obviously understood but that must be supplied to make a construction grammatically complete
- of a word or words that are superfluous or able to be understood from contextual clues
- a set of dots indicating an ellipsis

Author: toorielle
Content:

- another term for elliptic (= relating to or having the form of an ellipse)

Author: toorielle
Content: recrudesce [v.] - <FORMAL> break out again; recur

Author: toorielle
Content:
autophagy [n.] - <BIOLOGY> - consumption of the bodyâ€™s own tissue as a metabolic process occurring in starvation and certain diseases
- a cellular process where cells remove and recycle damaged or dysfunctional parts of themselves

Author: toorielle
Content:
prerogative [n.] - a right or privilege exclusive to a particular individual or class
- the right of the sovereign, which in British law is theoretically subject to no restriction
- a faculty or property distinguishing a person or class

Author: toorielle
Content:
stranglehold [n.] - a grip around the neck of another person that can kill by asphyxiation if held for long enough
- complete or overwhelming control

Author: toorielle
Content:
gentrification [n.] - the process whereby the character of a poor urban area is changed by wealthier people moving in, improving housing, and attracting new businesses, typically displacing current inhabitants in the process
- the process of making someone or something more refined, polite, or respectable

Author: toorielle
Content: translocate [v.] - <TECHNICAL> move from one place to another

Author: toorielle
Content: unstinting [adj.] - given or giving without restraint; unsparing

Author: toorielle
Content:
plurality [n.] - the fact or state of being plural
- a large number of people or things
- <US> the number of votes cast for a candidate who receives more than any other but does not receive an absolute majority
- <HISTORICAL> another term for pluralism

Author: toorielle
Content:
pluralism [n.] - a condition or system in which two or more states, groups, principles, sources of authority, etc., coexist
- a political theory or system of power-sharing among a number of political parties
- a theory or system of devolution and autonomy for individual bodies in preference to monolithic state control
- a form of society in which the members of minority groups maintain their independent cultural traditions
- <PHILOSOPHY> a theory or system that recognizes more than one ultimate principle
- the practice of holding more than one office or church benefice at a time

Author: toorielle
Content:
devolution [n.] - the transfer or delegation of power to a lower level, especially by central government to local or regional administration
- <FORMAL> descent or degeneration to a lower or worse state
- <LAW> the legal transfer of property from one owner to another
- <BIOLOGY> evolutionary degeneration

Author: toorielle
Content:
autogenous [adj.] - arising from within or from a thing itself
- (of welding) done either without solder (= a metal or metallic alloy used when melted to join metallic surfaces) or with a filler of the same metal as the pieces being welded

Author: toorielle
Content:
dictate [v.] - lay down authoritatively; prescribe
- say or read aloud (words to be typed, written down, or recorded on tape)
- [n.] - an order or principle that must be obeyed

Author: toorielle
Content:
impingement [n.] - intrusion into an area belonging to or affecting someone or something else
- <MEDICINE> a painful condition caused by rubbing or pressure on a tendon, nerve, etc., by adjacent structures

Author: toorielle
Content: tetanus [n.] - <MEDICINE> a serious bacterial infection that causes painful muscle spasms and can lead to death, contracted through a contaminated surface

Author: toorielle
Content:
prescriptive [adj.] - relating to the imposition or enforcement of a rule or method
- <LINGUISTICS> attempting to impose rules of correct usage on the users of a language
- (of a right, title, or institution) having become legally established or accepted by long usage or the passage of time
- <ARCHAIC> established by long-standing custom or usage

Author: toorielle
Content:
tract [n.] - an area of indefinite extent, typically a large one
- an indefinitely large extent of something
- a major passage in the body, large bundle of nerve fibers, or other continuous elongated anatomical structure or region
- a short treatise in pamphlet form, typically on a religious subject

Author: toorielle
Content: ethereality [n.] - the quality of being very light and delicate, especially in a way that does not seem to come from the real, physical world

Author: toorielle
Content: rebar [n.] - short for â€œreinforcing barâ€ or â€œreinforcement bar," a metal bar that is used to help increase the tensile strength of concrete

Author: toorielle
Content:
tensile [adj.] - relating to tension

Author: toorielle
Content: subjective well-being (SWB) [n.] - a concept in psychology that refers to an individual's assessment of their overall life satisfaction and feelings of happiness

Author: toorielle
Content:

Author: toorielle
Content:

- <FORMAL> provide support or a firm basis for

Author: toorielle
Content:
analgesic [adj.] - <MEDICINE> (of a drug) acting to relieve pain
- [n.] - an analgesic drug

Author: toorielle
Content:

Author: toorielle

Author: toorielle
Content: aniseed [n.] - the seed of the anise, used in cooking and herbal medicine

Author: toorielle

Author: toorielle

Author: toorielle
Content:
orderly [n.] - an attendant in a hospital responsible for the nonmedical care of patients and the maintenance of order and cleanliness

Author: toorielle
Content:
hermetically [adj.] - in a way that is completely airtight
- in a way that is insulated or protected from outside influences

Author: toorielle
Content: cabal [n.] - a secret political clique or faction

Author: toorielle
Content: aural [adj.] - relating to the ear or the sense of hearing

Author: toorielle
Content:
rite [n.] - a religious or other solemn ceremony or act
- a social custom, practice, or conventional act

Author: toorielle
Content: relegate [v.] - consign or dismiss to an inferior rank or position

Content:

Author: toorielle
Content:
dynastic [adj.] - relating to a line of hereditary rulers of a country

Content:

- cause (an action or process) to begin

Author: toorielle
Content:

Author: toorielle
Content:
clientelism [n.] - a social order that depends upon relations of patronage; in particular, a political approach that emphasizes or exploits such relations

Author: toorielle
Content: quid-pro-quo [n.] - a favor or advantage granted or expected in return for something

Author: toorielle
Content:
enclave [n.] - a territory that is entirely surrounded by the territory of only one other state or entity
- a distinct territorial, cultural, or social unit enclosed within or as if within foreign territory

Author: toorielle
Content:
feudalism [n.] - the dominant social system in medieval Europe, in which the nobility held lands from the Crown in exchange for military service, and vassals were in turn tenants of the nobles, while the peasants (villeins or serfs) were obliged to live on their lord's land and give him homage, labor, and a share of the produce, notionally in exchange for military protection
- "Basically a select few nobles own all the land. They let peasants live on the land and in exchange those peasants get to work on the farms there. The nobles take a big cut of the money generated from selling the crops and livestock raised on the farm and the peasants get enough food to live on. The nobles do this on behest of the king, to make controlling the country easier."

Author: toorielle
Content:
vassal [n.] - <HISTORICAL> a holder of land by feudal tenure on conditions of homage and allegiance
- a person or country in a subordinate position to another

Author: toorielle
Content:
pare [v.] - trim (something) by cutting away its outer edges
- cut off the outer skin of (something)
- reduce (something) in size, extent, quantity, or number, usually in a number of small successive stages

Author: toorielle
Content:
grassroots [adj.] - basic, fundamental 
- not adapted from or added to an existing facility or operation; totally new
- [n.] - uses the people in a given district, region or community as the basis for a political or continent movement
- grassroots movements are initiated and driven by ordinary citizens, rather than being top-down initiatives from politicians or influential leaders

Author: toorielle
Content:
national vision [n.] - a concept that determines the mid-term and long-term development goals of a country and provides the basis for the development of national strategies and implementation plans
- a long-term plan, usually spanning 20 years or more, that outlines a country's aspirations and goals for development

Author: toorielle
Content:
posturing [n.] - artificial or pretentious behavior intended to impress or deceive others
- behavior that is intended to impress or mislead

Author: toorielle
Content:
posture [v.] - behave in a way that is intended to impress or mislead
- adopt (a certain attitude) so as to impress or mislead
- <ARCHAIC> place (someone) in a particular attitude or pose

Author: toorielle
Content:

- emphasizes the sustainable management of resources for present and future generations

Author: toorielle
Content:

- the action or state of perforating or being perforated

Author: toorielle
Content:

- a complicated or confused situation

Author: toorielle
Content:

- <BIOLOGY> the fusion of reproductive cells from related individuals; inbreeding; self-pollination

Author: toorielle
Content:

Author: toorielle
Content: tableland [n.] - a broad, high level region; a plateau

Author: toorielle
Content:

- when sunlight from a planet lights the dark side of one of its moons
- the "dark side" of a celestial body being faintly illuminated by the sunlight reflected off another, like the Earth lighting up the Moon

Author: toorielle
Content:
infrastructure [n.] - the basic physical and organizational structures and facilities (e.g. buildings, roads, power supplies) needed for the operation of a society or enterprise
- the underlying foundation or basic framework (as of a system or organization)

Author: toorielle
Content: edict [n.] - an official order or proclamation issued by a person in authority

Content:
prana [n.] - <HINDUISM> breath, considered as a life-giving force
pranic [adj.] - relating to prana

Author: toorielle
Content: subliminal [adj.] - <PSYCHOLOGY> (of a stimulus or mental process) below the threshold of sensation or consciousness; perceived by or affecting someone's mind without their being aware of it

Author: toorielle

Author: toorielle
Content:

Author: toorielle
Content:
caravan [n.] - <HISTORICAL> a group of merchants, pilgrims, or travelers journeying together, usually for mutual protection in deserts or other hostile regions

-  covered horse-drawn wagon
- <NA> a covered truck; a van

Author: toorielle
Content:
peripatetic [adj.] - traveling from place to place, in particular working or based in various places for relatively short periods
[n.] - a person who travels from place to place

Author: toorielle
Content:

Author: toorielle
Content:

- (of people) inhabiting or existing in a land from the earliest times or from before the arrival of colonists

Author: toorielle

Author: toorielle

Author: toorielle
Content: ethnonym [n.] - a name used to refer to an ethnic group, tribe, or people

Author: toorielle
Content:

Author: toorielle
Content:
repeal [v.] - to rescind or annul by authoritative act, especially a law or congressional act
- abandon; renounce

Author: toorielle
Content:

- fine material used to bind together the coarser particles of a composite substance

Author: toorielle

Content:

SWANA [n] - stands for Southwest Asian and North African, a term used to describe a specific geographic region, often referred to as the "Middle East"

Author: toorielle

entrenched [adj.] - (of an attitude, habit, or belief) firmly established and difficult or unlikely to change; ingrained

Content:
abstract [v.] - consider (something) theoretically or separately from something else

- withdraw

- [n.] - a summary of the contents of a book, article, or formal speech

Author: toorielle
Content: â€œin the abstractâ€ [phrase] - in a general way; without reference to specific instances

Content:
skylark [n.] - a common Eurasian and North African lark of farmland and open country, noted for its prolonged song during hovering flight

Author: toorielle
Content:

Author: toorielle

Author: toorielle
Content:

Author: toorielle

It is often used to describe how individuals or groups are marginalized, discriminated against, or treated differently based on their race."

- mark (goods or a package) with a document or label listing the contents

Content:

Content:

- close, strict, or rigorous

Content:

Content:

Author: toorielle
Content:

Content:

Content:

Content:
